In Allen v. Cooper, SCOTUS recently upheld a Fourth Circuit ruling that the Copyright Remedy Clarification Act of 1990 (CRCA) does not validly abrogate state sovereign immunity under the 11th Amendment.
When North Carolina published some of Allen’s works on the state’s website, Allen objected, and the parties reached a settlement.
When North Carolina refused to admit wrongdoing, Allen filed suit in federal court for copyright infringement.
First, Congress must have enacted “unequivocal statutory language” abrogating the States’ immunity from the suit….
Here are three takeaways from Allen v. Cooper that should help put such thoughts into perspective:States Can Be Still Be (Kind Of) Sued For Copyright Infringement.